--- !u!114 &2056919942
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 2056919941}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: d465e30aa1b52df429ad5765eba7c4ee, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: '::'
  panel: {fileID: 1022314586}
  explanationText: {fileID: 203552883}
  scrollRect: {fileID: 105671769}
  explanations:
  - "Helloooooo, tiny carbon-based lifeform!\r\n\r\nI\u2019m\u2026 uh\u2026 still
    workshopping my name. Let\u2019s go with Professor Boom-Atom for now.\r\n\r\nToday\u2019s
    experiment looks like magic\u2026\r\nbut it\u2019s actually SCIENCE DOING A HAPPY
    DANCE!\r\n\r\nInside that tube, you poured vinegar \u2014 that\u2019s an acid.\r\nAnd
    inside the balloon? Baking soda \u2014 that\u2019s a base.\r\n\r\nWhen they meet,
    they create a gas called carbon dioxide.\r\n\r\nAnd guess what gas LOVES to do?\r\n\r\nEXPAND.
    LIKE. CRAZY.\r\n\r\nAs the gas fills the balloon, it pushes outward\u2026\r\nand
    BOOM \u2014 the balloon grows!\r\n\r\nBut this isn\u2019t random chaos.\r\n\r\nIt\u2019s
    called an acid-base reaction,\r\nand it happens all over nature.\r\n\r\nEven
    in your stomach.\r\nWhich is\u2026 slightly less exciting.\r\n\r\nSo what did
    we learn?\r\n\r\n\u2022 Mixing substances can create new ones  \r\n\u2022 Gases
    take up space  \r\n\u2022 Science is basically invisible explosions you\u2019re
    allowed to do  \r\n\r\nStick with me, kid.\r\n\r\nWe\u2019re just getting started."
  - "Helloooo again, tiny carbon-based lifeform!\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom is back\u2014and
    this time\u2026 we\u2019re putting out fire\u2026 without touching it.\n\nSuspicious?
    Good. Stay curious.\n\nSo here\u2019s what you did.\n\nYou placed a candle in
    a cup\u2026 added baking soda around it\u2026 lit the flame\u2026 and then poured
    vinegar on top.\n\nLooks harmless.\n\nBut behind the scenes?\n\nSCIENCE IS PREPARING
    A SNEAK ATTACK.\n\nWhen vinegar and baking soda meet, they react\u2014just like
    before.\n\nBut this time, we\u2019re not here for balloons.\n\nWe\u2019re here
    for something invisible.\n\nThey produce\u2026 carbon dioxide gas.\n\nNow here\u2019s
    the important part.\n\nFire needs three things to survive:\nheat, fuel\u2026
    and oxygen.\n\nTake away even one\u2026\n\nand the flame goes out.\n\nCarbon
    dioxide is heavier than air.\n\nSo instead of floating away\u2026\n\nit pours
    down, like an invisible blanket.\n\nIt spreads over the candle\u2026\n\npushes
    the oxygen away\u2026\n\nand suddenly\u2014\n\npoof.\n\nNo oxygen\u2026\n\nno
    fire.\n\nExtinguished.\n\nAnd the best part?\n\nYou didn\u2019t blow it out.\nYou
    didn\u2019t touch it.\n\nYou just changed the air around it.\n\nThat\u2019s powerful.\n\nThis
    is the same idea behind real fire extinguishers.\n\nSome of them release carbon
    dioxide to suffocate flames safely.\n\nSo what did we learn?\n\nFire isn\u2019t
    magic\u2014it\u2019s chemistry.\n\nGases can move and spread even when we can\u2019t
    see them.\n\nAnd sometimes\u2026\n\nthe most powerful tools are completely invisible.\n\nKeep
    watching closely, scientist.\n\nThe air around you is doing more than you think."
  - "Helloooooo, moisture enthusiast!\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today
    we\u2019re about to make water\u2026 disappear.\n\nNo tricks. No towels.\n\nJust
    science doing something VERY strange.\n\nSo here\u2019s what you did.\n\nYou
    took some water\u2026 added red dye to make it easier to see\u2026 and poured
    it into a beaker with crystal powder.\n\nLooks simple.\n\nBut those tiny crystals?\n\nThey
    are NOT what they seem.\n\nThey\u2019re made of a special material called a polymer.\n\nAnd
    polymers are like tiny molecular sponges.\n\nBut not the kind you wash dishes
    with.\n\nOh no.\n\nThese things are built to absorb water on a MASSIVE scale.\n\nWhen
    the colored water touches the crystals\u2026\n\nthe water molecules get pulled
    inside them.\n\nLocked in.\n\nTrapped between long chains of molecules that stretch
    and expand.\n\nAnd as more water gets absorbed\u2026\n\nthe crystals swell up\u2026\n\nand
    up\u2026\n\nand up\u2026\n\nuntil\u2014\n\npoof.\n\nThe liquid is gone.\n\nBut
    don\u2019t be fooled.\n\nIt didn\u2019t vanish.\n\nIt\u2019s still there.\n\nJust
    stored inside the polymer as a squishy, gel-like substance.\n\nYou\u2019ve basically
    turned liquid water\u2026\n\ninto a solid-like material.\n\nWILD.\n\nThis is
    called absorption.\n\nNot to be confused with adsorption\u2014which is a whole
    other scientific party.\n\nThese polymers are called superabsorbent materials.\n\nThey\u2019re
    used in things like diapers, soil for plants, and even medical products.\n\nSo
    what did we learn?\n\nSome materials can trap huge amounts of water.\n\nLiquids
    can be transformed into gels.\n\nAnd science can make things disappear\u2026\n\nwithout
    actually making them disappear.\n\nStick with me, scientist.\n\nWe\u2019re just
    getting warmed up."
  - "Helloooo, brave experimenter.\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today we
    are about to create a reaction so energetic, it looks like a giant creature is
    brushing its teeth.\n\nBut don\u2019t be fooled.\n\nThis isn\u2019t toothpaste.\n\nThis
    is chemistry moving very, very fast.\n\nSo here\u2019s what you did.\n\nYou poured
    hydrogen peroxide into the flask, added dish soap, mixed some yeast with water,
    and then combined everything together.\n\nAt first, it seems calm.\n\nBut the
    moment the yeast mixture hits the hydrogen peroxide\u2026\n\neverything changes.\n\nHydrogen
    peroxide is a molecule made of hydrogen and oxygen.\n\nIt naturally wants to
    break down into water and oxygen gas.\n\nBut on its own, it does this very slowly.\n\nThat\u2019s
    where the yeast comes in.\n\nYeast contains something called an enzyme\u2014specifically,
    catalase.\n\nAnd catalase is extremely good at breaking apart hydrogen peroxide.\n\nSo
    when you add the yeast\u2026\n\nit acts like a chemical accelerator.\n\nSuddenly,
    the hydrogen peroxide starts breaking down rapidly into water and oxygen gas.\n\nAnd
    that oxygen gas?\n\nIt forms bubbles.\n\nLots and lots of bubbles.\n\nNow remember
    the dish soap you added earlier?\n\nThat soap traps the oxygen bubbles, turning
    them into foam.\n\nSo instead of gas escaping invisibly\u2026\n\nyou get a huge,
    expanding tower of bubbly foam bursting out of the flask.\n\nFast.\n\nMessy.\n\nSpectacular.\n\nAnd
    there\u2019s one more thing.\n\nThis reaction releases heat.\n\nThat means it\u2019s
    an exothermic reaction.\n\nSo the foam isn\u2019t just growing\u2026\n\nit\u2019s
    actually warm.\n\nSo what did we learn?\n\nSome reactions can be sped up using
    catalysts like enzymes.\n\nGases can create visible structures when trapped in
    liquids.\n\nAnd chemistry can turn something simple into something explosive\u2014without
    any fire at all.\n\nCareful, scientist.\n\nThings are starting to get intense."
  - "Helloooo, curious chemist.\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today we\u2019re
    turning a humble fruit\u2026 into a tiny erupting volcano.\n\nNo lava flows,
    no tectonic plates\u2026\n\nbut plenty of bubbling chaos.\n\nSo here\u2019s what
    you did.\n\nYou cut the top and bottom of a lemon, scooped out some of the inside,
    added red food coloring, sprinkled in baking soda, and gave it a poke.\n\nAt
    first, it just looks like a messy citrus snack.\n\nBut inside that lemon?\n\nThere\u2019s
    something powerful hiding.\n\nLemons are full of citric acid.\n\nThat means the
    inside of the lemon is already acidic\u2014just like the vinegar from earlier
    experiments.\n\nWhen you add baking soda, which is a base\u2026\n\nyou\u2019re
    setting up an acid-base reaction.\n\nThe moment they come into contact\u2026\n\nthey
    react and produce carbon dioxide gas.\n\nAnd just like before\u2026\n\nthat gas
    wants to escape.\n\nFast.\n\nThe bubbles build up, push through the liquid\u2026\n\nand
    suddenly\u2014\n\nyou get a fizzy, foamy eruption bursting out of the lemon.\n\nThat\u2019s
    your volcano.\n\nThe red dye makes it look like lava, but what you\u2019re really
    seeing is gas forcing liquid upward.\n\nPressure builds.\n\nGas expands.\n\nAnd
    the only way out\u2026\n\nis up.\n\nSo what did we learn?\n\nAcids and bases
    can react to produce gas.\n\nNatural materials\u2014like fruit\u2014can act as
    part of a chemical reaction.\n\nAnd even something as simple as a lemon can become
    a miniature volcano with the right ingredients.\n\nStay sharp, scientist.\n\nEven
    the smallest things can erupt with the right chemistry."
  - "Helloooo, deep-sea scientist.\r\n\r\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today
    we\u2019re creating a volcano\u2026 underwater.\r\n\r\nNo fire. No lava.\r\n\r\nJust
    layers, density, and a very dramatic chemical reaction.\r\n\r\nSo here\u2019s
    what you did.\r\n\r\nYou added water to a test tube, mixed in red dye, dropped
    in some baking soda, poured in oil, and finally added citric acid.\r\n\r\nAt
    first, everything looks calm.\r\n\r\nBut take a closer look.\r\n\r\nThe oil and
    water don\u2019t mix.\r\n\r\nWhy?\r\n\r\nBecause water is polar\u2014it has charged
    regions\u2014while oil is nonpolar.\r\n\r\nThey simply don\u2019t get along.\r\n\r\nSo
    the oil floats on top, forming a separate layer.\r\n\r\nNow inside the water
    layer, the baking soda is waiting.\r\n\r\nThe moment you add citric acid\u2026\r\n\r\nyou
    trigger an acid-base reaction.\r\n\r\nJust like before.\r\n\r\nThey react and
    produce carbon dioxide gas.\r\n\r\nBut this time, something different happens.\r\n\r\nThe
    gas forms bubbles inside the colored water\u2026\r\n\r\nand those bubbles rise
    upward.\r\n\r\nAs they rise, they carry bits of the red liquid with them.\r\n\r\nThey
    push through the oil layer\u2026\r\n\r\nand burst at the top.\r\n\r\nThen the
    liquid falls back down.\r\n\r\nOver and over again.\r\n\r\nIt looks like a lava
    lamp\u2026\r\n\r\nor an underwater volcano erupting again and again.\r\n\r\nWhat
    you\u2019re seeing is a combination of three things.\r\n\r\nA chemical reaction
    producing gas.\r\n\r\nDensity differences between liquids.\r\n\r\nAnd bubbles
    acting like tiny elevators, lifting liquid upward.\r\n\r\nSo what did we learn?\r\n\r\nSome
    liquids don\u2019t mix because of their molecular structure.\r\n\r\nGas bubbles
    can move liquids through different layers.\r\n\r\nAnd chemical reactions can
    create motion\u2014not just change.\r\n\r\nKeep observing, scientists.\r\n\r\nSometimes
    the most interesting eruptions don\u2019t involve fire at all.\r\n"
  - "Helloooo, fearless experimenter.\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today
    we\u2019re summoning a creature that looks alive\u2026 but is made entirely of
    chemistry.\n\nNo scales. No muscles.\n\nJust fire\u2026 and transformation.\n\nSo
    here\u2019s what you did.\n\nYou mixed sugar and baking soda, prepared a bed
    of sand, poured ethanol onto it, placed the mixture on top, and then lit it.\n\nAt
    first, you see a flame.\n\nThat\u2019s the ethanol burning.\n\nEthanol is a fuel,
    and when it reacts with oxygen in the air, it produces heat.\n\nLots of it.\n\nBut
    the real magic happens because of what that heat does.\n\nThe heat spreads into
    the sugar and baking soda mixture.\n\nSugar, when heated, starts to break apart.\n\nIt
    decomposes.\n\nInstead of melting cleanly, it turns into carbon and releases
    gases.\n\nAt the same time, the baking soda is also breaking down.\n\nIt produces
    carbon dioxide gas when heated.\n\nSo now you have two things happening together.\n\nSolid
    material is turning into carbon.\n\nAnd gas is being released from inside it.\n\nThat
    gas pushes outward, expanding the hot carbon as it forms.\n\nSlowly at first\u2026\n\nthen
    more dramatically\u2026\n\na black, foamy structure begins to grow.\n\nIt curls,
    stretches, and rises upward like a snake emerging from the sand.\n\nBut it\u2019s
    not alive.\n\nIt\u2019s carbon being shaped by escaping gas.\n\nThe more gas
    produced, the more it expands and twists.\n\nThe flame keeps feeding heat into
    the reaction\u2026\n\nand the snake keeps growing.\n\nSo what did we learn?\n\nHeat
    can break down materials into new substances.\n\nGases can shape solids as they
    form.\n\nAnd chemical reactions can create structures that look almost alive\u2026\n\neven
    when they\u2019re not.\n\nCareful, scientist.\n\nNot everything that moves\u2026
    is living."
  - "Helloooo, color-mixing mastermind.\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today
    we\u2019re building something hypnotic.\n\nNo flames. No explosions.\n\nJust
    bubbles, color, and motion that refuses to sit still.\n\nSo here\u2019s what
    you did.\n\nYou added water to a beaker, mixed in citric acid, then red and yellow
    dye, poured in vegetable oil, and finally added baking soda.\n\nAt first, it
    looks like layers.\n\nThat\u2019s because oil and water don\u2019t mix.\n\nWater
    is polar\u2014its molecules have slight charges.\n\nOil is nonpolar.\n\nSo instead
    of blending together, the oil floats on top of the water.\n\nTwo separate worlds
    in one container.\n\nNow inside the water layer, the citric acid is already dissolved.\n\nWhen
    you add baking soda\u2026\n\nthe reaction begins.\n\nAcid meets base.\n\nAnd
    just like before, they produce carbon dioxide gas.\n\nBut here\u2019s where it
    gets interesting.\n\nThe gas forms bubbles in the colored water.\n\nThose bubbles
    rise upward\u2026\n\ndragging bits of the colored liquid with them.\n\nThey push
    through the oil layer\u2026\n\nreach the top\u2026\n\nand then the gas escapes.\n\nWithout
    the gas, the colored liquid becomes heavier again.\n\nSo it sinks back down.\n\nAnd
    the cycle repeats.\n\nUp.\n\nDown.\n\nOver and over again.\n\nIt looks like blobs
    of glowing lava floating through the liquid.\n\nBut what you\u2019re really seeing
    is a balance between density and gas movement.\n\nThe oil stays on top because
    it\u2019s less dense.\n\nThe water stays below because it\u2019s more dense.\n\nAnd
    the gas bubbles act like tiny elevators, lifting and dropping the colored liquid
    again and again.\n\nSo what did we learn?\n\nSome liquids won\u2019t mix because
    of their molecular structure.\n\nGases can move liquids in surprising ways.\n\nAnd
    when chemistry meets density\u2026\n\nyou get motion that feels almost alive.\n\nKeep
    watching, scientist.\n\nSometimes the calmest setups create the most mesmerizing
    results."
  - "Helloooo, purification specialist.\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today
    we\u2019re taking something dirty\u2026 and making it clean.\n\nNo magic spells.
    No invisible force fields.\n\nJust layers, particles, and a very clever setup.\n\nSo
    here\u2019s what you did.\n\nYou built a filtration system using cotton, sand,
    charcoal, gravel, and stones.\n\nThen you poured dirty water through it.\n\nAt
    first glance, it just looks like a stack of materials.\n\nBut each layer has
    a job.\n\nThe larger materials\u2014stones and gravel\u2014catch the biggest
    pieces first.\n\nBits of dirt, debris, anything chunky.\n\nThey act like the
    first line of defense.\n\nNext comes sand.\n\nSand traps smaller particles that
    slipped through the top layers.\n\nThings you might not even notice with your
    eyes.\n\nThen comes charcoal.\n\nAnd this is where things get interesting.\n\nCharcoal
    doesn\u2019t just trap particles.\n\nIt absorbs certain impurities\u2014tiny
    molecules that cause color, odor, or unwanted chemicals.\n\nIt\u2019s like a
    molecular sponge.\n\nFinally, the cotton acts as a fine filter.\n\nCatching the
    smallest remaining particles before the water exits.\n\nAs the dirty water passes
    through each layer\u2026\n\nit gets cleaner and cleaner.\n\nNot because anything
    disappeared\u2026\n\nbut because unwanted materials were removed step by step.\n\nSo
    what comes out the bottom looks much clearer.\n\nBut remember\u2026\n\nclear
    doesn\u2019t always mean safe to drink.\n\nThere can still be microscopic organisms
    or dissolved substances that this system doesn\u2019t remove.\n\nSo what did
    we learn?\n\nFiltration works by separating materials based on size and properties.\n\nDifferent
    layers can target different types of impurities.\n\nAnd clean-looking water isn\u2019t
    always completely clean.\n\nStay sharp, scientist.\n\nSometimes what you can\u2019t
    see\u2026 matters the most."
  - "Helloooo, energy explorer.\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today we\u2019re
    turning fruit\u2026 into electricity.\n\nYes. Fruit.\n\nNo power outlet. No batteries
    from a store.\n\nJust lemons\u2026 and chemistry.\n\nSo here\u2019s what you
    did.\n\nYou connected lemons in a chain using copper wire and nails, attached
    red and black wires, and connected everything to an LED.\n\nAt first, it looks
    impossible.\n\nHow can a lemon power anything?\n\nBut inside each lemon, something
    important is happening.\n\nLemons contain an acidic liquid filled with ions\u2014tiny
    charged particles that can move.\n\nWhen you insert two different metals into
    that environment\u2014like copper and a nail\u2014you create a chemical difference
    between them.\n\nEach metal reacts differently with the acid.\n\nThis creates
    a buildup of electrical energy.\n\nOne metal becomes more negative.\n\nThe other
    becomes more positive.\n\nAnd nature really doesn\u2019t like that imbalance.\n\nSo
    electrons begin to move.\n\nThey flow from one metal to the other through the
    wire.\n\nThat movement of electrons\u2026\n\nis electricity.\n\nEach lemon produces
    a small amount of voltage.\n\nNot enough to do much on its own.\n\nBut when you
    connect multiple lemons together\u2026\n\ntheir voltages add up.\n\nNow you have
    enough energy to power something small\u2014like an LED.\n\nThe light turns on\u2026\n\nnot
    because of magic\u2026\n\nbut because electrons are flowing in a complete circuit.\n\nFrom
    one lemon\u2026\n\nto the next\u2026\n\nthrough the wire\u2026\n\nand back again.\n\nSo
    what did we learn?\n\nChemical reactions can generate electrical energy.\n\nDifferent
    materials can create voltage when placed in an electrolyte.\n\nAnd electricity
    isn\u2019t something that only comes from outlets\u2026\n\nit can be created
    from simple, natural materials.\n\nStay energized, scientist.\n\nThe power around
    you is more accessible than you think."
  - "Helloooo, texture engineer.\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today we\u2019re
    making something that\u2019s not quite a liquid\u2026 and not quite a solid.\n\nIt
    stretches. It squishes.\n\nIt refuses to pick a side.\n\nSo here\u2019s what
    you did.\n\nYou prepared two mixtures.\n\nIn one cup, you dissolved borax in
    water.\n\nIn another, you mixed glue with water.\n\nOn their own, both of these
    look completely normal.\n\nBut the moment you combine them\u2026\n\neverything
    changes.\n\nGlue is made of long chains of molecules called polymers.\n\nNormally,
    these chains can slide past each other easily, which is why glue flows like a
    liquid.\n\nBut when you add borax\u2026\n\nit acts like a connector.\n\nIt links
    those long polymer chains together.\n\nNot in one solid block\u2026\n\nbut in
    a flexible network.\n\nNow the chains can\u2019t move freely anymore.\n\nThey\u2019re
    tied together at multiple points.\n\nThis creates something new.\n\nA material
    that can stretch when you pull it\u2026\n\nbut still hold together instead of
    flowing apart.\n\nThat\u2019s slime.\n\nWhen you move it slowly, it stretches
    and behaves like a thick liquid.\n\nBut if you pull it quickly, it resists and
    feels more solid.\n\nIt\u2019s what we call a non-Newtonian material.\n\nIts
    behavior changes depending on how you interact with it.\n\nSo what did we learn?\n\nPolymers
    can change properties when their structure is altered.\n\nCross-linking molecules
    can transform a liquid into a stretchy, semi-solid material.\n\nAnd some materials
    don\u2019t follow the usual rules of solids and liquids.\n\nCareful, scientist.\n\nNot
    everything fits neatly into categories."
  - "Helloooo, temperature tracker.\n\nProfessor Boom-Atom here\u2014and today we\u2019re
    building a device that can sense something you can\u2019t even see.\n\nTemperature.\n\nNo
    electronics. No digital screens.\n\nJust liquid\u2026 air\u2026 and expansion.\n\nSo
    here\u2019s what you did.\n\nYou marked a straw, sealed it into a bottle using
    clay, filled the bottle with rubbing alcohol and food coloring, and connected
    everything so the liquid could rise into the straw.\n\nAt first, it just looks
    like colored liquid sitting still.\n\nBut this setup is very sensitive to change.\n\nRubbing
    alcohol expands when it gets warmer.\n\nThat means as temperature increases\u2026\n\nthe
    molecules inside the liquid move faster and spread out.\n\nWhen that happens,
    the liquid needs more space.\n\nBut the bottle is sealed.\n\nSo the only place
    the liquid can go\u2026\n\nis up the straw.\n\nAs it rises, you can see the level
    change against your markings.\n\nThat\u2019s your thermometer.\n\nNow when the
    temperature drops\u2026\n\nthe opposite happens.\n\nThe molecules slow down.\n\nThey
    take up less space.\n\nAnd the liquid level falls back down.\n\nSo without using
    any electronics\u2026\n\nyou\u2019ve built a system that translates invisible
    temperature changes into visible movement.\n\nThe straw acts as a narrow pathway,
    making even small changes easier to see.\n\nAnd the colored liquid helps you
    track it clearly.\n\nSo what did we learn?\n\nTemperature affects how fast molecules
    move.\n\nMaterials expand when heated and contract when cooled.\n\nAnd with the
    right setup\u2026\n\nyou can measure something invisible using simple physical
    changes.\n\nStay observant, scientist.\n\nThe world is constantly changing\u2014even
    when you can\u2019t see it."
  typingSpeed: 0.08
  audioSource: {fileID: 2056919944}
  blipSound: {fileID: 8300000, guid: 6148935eff932464690b8a1e4e8ad9c9, type: 3}
